ant.jpg|80px]]\n| [[Professor]] [[Mark Oliphant|Sir Mark Oliphant]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC|KBE}}\n| 1 December 1971\n| 30 November 1976\n| {{age in years and days|1971|12|01|1976|11|30}}\n|-\n| 28\n| [[Image:Douglas nicholls.jpg|80px]]\n| [[Douglas Nicholls|Sir Douglas Nicholls]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|KCVO|OBE}}\n| 1 December 1976\n| 30 April 1977\n| {{age in years and days|1976|12|01|1977|04|30}}\n|-\n| 29\n| [[Image:Badge of the Governor of South Australia.svg|80px]]\n| [[Reverend]] [[Keith Seaman|Sir Keith Seaman]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|KCVO|OBE}}\n| 1 September 1977\n| 28 March 1982\n| {{age in years and days|1977|09|01|1982|03|28}}\n|-\n| 30\n| [[Image:Badge of the Governor of South Australia.svg|80px]]\n| [[Lieutenant general (Australia)|Lieutenant General]] [[Donald Dunstan (governor)|Sir Donald Dunstan]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC|KBE|CB}}\n| 23 April 1982\n| 5 February 1991\n| '''{{age in years and days|1982|04|23|1991|02|05}}'''\n|-\n| 31\n| [[Image:Roma Mitchell 1965.jpg|80px]]\n| [[The Honourable|The Hon.]] [[Roma Mitchell|Dame Roma Mitchell]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC|DBE|CVO|QC}}\n| 6 February 1991\n| 21 July 1996\n| {{age in years and days|1991|02|06|1996|07|21}}\n|-\n| 32\n| [[Image:Sir Eric Neal in Adelaide, South Australia 2016.jpg|80px]]\n| [[Eric Neal|Sir Eric Neal]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC|CVO}}\n| 22 July 1996\n| 3 November 2001\n| {{age in years and days|1996|07|22|2001|11|03}}\n|-\n| 33\n| [[Image:Marjorie Jackson.jpg|80px]]\n| [[Marjorie Jackson-Nelson]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC|CVO|MBE}}\n| 3 November 2001\n| 31 July 2007\n| {{age in years and days|2001|11|03|2007|07|03}}\n|-\n| 34\n| [[Image:Kevin Scarce in 2008.jpg|80px]]\n| [[Rear admiral (Australia)|Rear Admiral]] [[The Honourable|The Hon.]] [[Kevin Scarce]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC|CSC}}\n| 8 August 2007\n| 7 August 2014\n| {{age in years and days|2007|08|08|2014|08|07}}\n|-\n| 35\n| [[Image:Hieu Van Le 2015.jpg|80px]]\n| [[The Honourable|The Hon.]] [[Hieu Van Le]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS||sep=,|AC}}\n| 1 September 2014\n| present\n| {{age in years and days|2014|09|01}}\n|}\n\n==Administrators and Lieutenant-Governors==\nThese people administered the government in the absence of the official governor.<ref name=\"table a\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Administrator !!Term\n|-\n|-\n| [[George Milner Stephen]] || 1838 \n|-\n| [[Boyle Travers Finniss]] || 1854-55 \n|-\n| Lt.-Col. [[Francis Gilbert Hamley]] || 1868-69 \n|-\n| Major [[James Harwood Rocke]] || 1870 \n|-\n| Hon. Sir [[Richard Davies Hanson]], Chief Justice || 1872-73 \n|-\n| Sir [[William Wellington Cairns]], K.C.M.G || 1877 \n|-\n| Hon. [[Samuel James Way]], Chief Justice, Lt.-Gov. || 1877 to 1915 (on 65 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[James Penn Boucaut]], Judge of Supreme Court || 1885, 1886, 1888, 1890, 1891, 1897 \n|-\n| Hon. [[William Henry Bundey]], Judge of Supreme Court || 1888 \n|-\n| Hon. Sir [[George John Robert Murray]], Chief Justice,  Lt.-Gov.||1916\u201324, 1926\u201342 (on 103 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[Thomas Slaney Poole]], Judge of Supreme Court|| 1925 (on 2 occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. Sir [[Herbert Angas Parsons]],  Judge of Supreme Court || 1935 to 1942 (on 6 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. Sir [[John Mellis Napier]], Chief Justice, Lt.-Gov.|| 1942 to 1973 (on 179 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. Sir [[Herbert Mayo (judge)|Herbert Mayo]], Judge of Supreme Court || 1946 to 1965 (on 25 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. Sir [[Geoffrey Sandford Reed]], Judge of Supreme Court || 1951 to 1957 (on 5 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[John Jefferson Bray]], Chief Justice|| 1968 to 1973 (on 8 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[David Stirling Hogarth]], Judge of Supreme Court || 1971 \n|-\n| [[Walter Crocker|Sir Walter Crocker]], Lt.-Gov. || 1973 to 1982 (on 29 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[Condor Laucke|Sir Condor Laucke]], Lt.-Gov. ||  1982 to 1992 (on 43 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[Leonard James King]], A.C., Chief Justice ||  1987 \n|-\n| Hon. Dr. [[Basil Hetzel]], Lt.-Gov. ||  1992 to 2000 (on 32 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[John Doyle (judge)|John Doyle]], Chief Justice ||  1999-2012 (on 10 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[Bruno Krumins]],  Lt.-Gov. ||  2000-2007 (on 60 separate occasions) \n|-\n| Hon. [[John William Perry]], Judge of Supreme Court  || 2002 \n|-\n| Hon. [[Hieu Van Le]], Lt.-Gov.  || 2007\u20132014 \n|-\n| Hon. [[Brenda Wilson]], Lt.-Gov.  || 2014\u2013date\n|}\n\n==Living former governors==\nThree former governors are alive, the oldest being [[Eric Neal|Sir Eric Neal]] (1996\u20132001, born 1924). The latest-serving former governor to die was [[Roma Mitchell|Dame Roma Mitchell]] (1991\u20131996), on 5 March 2000. The most recent death of a former governor was that of [[Keith Seaman|Sir Keith Seaman]] (1977-1982), on 30 June 2013.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name!!Term as governor!!Date of birth\n|-\n|[[Eric Neal|Sir Eric Neal]]\n|1996\u20132001\n|{{birth date and age|df=y|1924|6|3}}\n|-\n|[[Marjorie Jackson-Nelson]]\n|2001\u20132007\n|{{birth date and age|df=y|1931|9|13}}\n|-\n|Rear Admiral [[Kevin Scarce]]\n|2007\u20132014\n|{{birth date and age|df=y|1952|5|4}}\n|}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Governors of South Australia}}\n* [http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/ The Official Website of the Governor of South Australia]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071009122355/http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/html/governor.html#prev#prev Previous governors on official website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Governors of South Australia}}\n{{Australian governors}}\n{{Representatives of the monarch in Commonwealth realms and Dominions}}\n{{Politics of South Australia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Governor Of South Australia}}\n[[Category:Governors of South Australia|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of viceroys in Australia|South Australia]]\n[[Category:Parliament of South Australia]]\n[[Category:South Australia-related lists]]\n[[Category:1836 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Muzi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Governor_of_South_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Industry of Pakistan", "text_new": "Pakistan's industrial sector accounts for about 64% of GDP. Cotton textile production and apparel manufacturing are Pakistan's largest industries, accounting for about 65% of the merchandise exports and almost 40% of the employed labour force.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\">http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2006/05/23/000012009_20060523095241/Rendered/PDF/354991PK0rev0pdf.pdf</ref> Cotton and cotton-based products account for 61% of export earnings of Pakistan. The consumption of cotton increased by 5.7% over the past five years while the economic growth rate was 7%. By 2010 the spinning capacity increased to 15 million spindles and textile exports hit $15.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Bank Archives |url=https://wits.worldbank.org/CountryProfile/en/Country/PAK/Year/2010/Summarytext |website=worldbank.org |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> Other major industries include cement, fertilizer, edible oil, sugar, steel, tobacco, chemicals, machinery and food processing.\n\nThe government is [[privatization|privatizing]] large-scale parastatal units, and the public sector accounts for a shrinking proportion of industrial output, while growth in overall industrial output (including the private sector) has accelerated. Government policies aim to diversify the country's industrial base and bolster export industries.\n\n==Mining and quarrying==\nThe country has immense reserves of various minerals and natural resources.  Important minerals found in Pakistan are [[gypsum]], [[limestone]], [[chromite]]s, [[iron ore]], rock salt, [[silver]], [[gold]], precious stones, [[gemstone|gem]]s, marble, [[copper]], [[coal]], [[graphite]], [[sulphur]], fire clay, [[silica]]. The salt range in Punjab Province has one of the largest deposit of pure salt founded in the world. [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]] province is a mineral-rich area having substantial mineral, oil and gas reserves which have not been exploited to their full capacity or fully explored, recent government policies have begun to develop this region of the country and to tap into the immense resources found there. The province has significant quantities of copper, chromite and iron, and pockets of antimony and zinc in the south and gold in the far west. Natural gas was discovered near Sui in 1952, and the province has been gradually developing its oil and gas projects over the past fifty years.<ref name=\"minerals\">{{cite web|url=http://www.himalmag.com/2002/july/profile_2.htm|title=Himala South Asian, Pakistan Edition|publisher=|access-date=2008-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021155040/http://himalmag.com/2002/july/profile_2.htm|archive-date=2007-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMajor reserves of copper and gold in Balochistan's [[Reko Diq]] area have been discovered in early 2006. The Reko Diq mining area has proven estimated reserves of 2 billion tons of copper and 20 million ounces of gold. According to the current market price, the value of the deposits has been estimated at about $65 billion, which would generate thousands of jobs.\n\nThe discovery has ranked Rekodiq among the world's top seven copper reserves. The Rekodiq project is estimated to produce 200,000 tons of copper and 400,000 ounces of gold per year, at an estimated value of $1.25 billion at current market prices. The copper and gold are currently traded at about $5,000 per ton and $600 per ounce respectively in the international market.<ref>http://www.pakpositive.com/common/clicks/out2.php?pakpositive=%3A%2F%2Fwww.dawn.com%2F2006%2F04%2F14%2Ftop8.htm\n</ref>\n[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Province]] accounts for at least 78% of the marble production in Pakistan. Pakistan is home to some of the most finest and purest grades of marble, granite and slate found in the world.  Much of the grades A Marble that is exported out of European countries like Italy actually have their origins in Pakistan which previously lacked fine polishing and processing machinery.  The Government has taken steps to invest in this crucial sector with the recent establishment of a ''Marble City'' within Balochistan.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/>69\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued this sector at Rs.211,851 million in 2005 thus registering over 99% growth since 2000.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">https://web.archive.org/web/20070619224443/http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/fbs/statistics/national_accounts/table4.pdf</ref>\n\n==Fuel extraction industry==\n{{Main|Fuel extraction in Pakistan}}\nPakistan's first [[oil field]] was discovered in the late 1952 in Balochistan near a giant [[gas field]] at suo [[Sui, Balochistan|Sui]] in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]]. The [[Toot oilfield]] was discovered in the early 1960s Islamabad in the Punjab. Production has steadily increased since then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakpositive.com/2005/01/06/canadian-firm-to-develop-pakistan-oilfield/|title=Canadian Firm to Develop Pakistan Oilfield - PakPositive|website=www.pakpositive.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Pakistan]]'s first gas field was the giant [[gas field]] at Sui in Balochistan which was discovered in the late 1952.\n<ref>https://archive.today/20070528143233/http://www.pakistan.gov.pk/divisions/ContentInfo.jsp?DivID=49&cPath=768_867&ContentID=5217\n</ref>\nPakistan is also a major producer of  Bituminous coal, Sub-bituminous coal and Lignite. Coal mining started in the British colonial era and has continued to be used by Pakistani industries after independence in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://islamabad.usembassy.gov/pakistan/h07091701.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102175405/http://islamabad.usembassy.gov/pakistan/h07091701.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 November 2007|title=USTDA Grant To Support Integrated Coal Mining, Power Generation Project In Pakistan - U.S. Embassy Islamabad Pakistan|date=2 November 2007|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakistaneconomist.com/database2/cover/c2001-41.asp|title=Page not found - Pakistan & Gulf Economist|author=|date=|website=Pakistan & Gulf Economist}}</ref>\n\nPakistan produced about 45 tonnes of Uranium in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/inf23.html|title=World Uranium Mining 2016 - World Nuclear Association|website=www.world-nuclear.org}}</ref>\n\n==Manufacturing==\nIn FY 2002\u201303, real growth in manufacturing was 7.7%. In the twelve months ending 30 June 2004, large-scale manufacturing grew by more than 18% compared to the previous twelve-month period. The textile and garment industry's share in the economy along with its contribution to exports, employment, foreign-exchange earnings, investment and value added make it Pakistan's single largest manufacturing sector. The industry comprises 453 textile mills: 50 integrated units; and 403 spinning units, with 9.33 million spindles and 148,000 rotors, The capacity utilization was 83% for spindles and 47% for rotors during 2003.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/>\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued large-scale manufacturing at Rs.981,518 million in 2005 thus registering over 138% growth since 2000 <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/fbs/statistics/national_accounts/table4.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070619224443/http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/fbs/statistics/national_accounts/table4.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 June 2007|title=Wayback Machine|date=19 June 2007|publisher=}}</ref> while small-scale manufacturing was valued at Rs.356,835 million in 2005 thus registering over 80% growth since 2000.\n\n==Automotive Industry==\n'''[[Automotive industry in Pakistan|Pakistan's automotive industry]]''' is the one of the fastest growing industries of the country, accounting for 4% of Pakistan's GDP and employing a [[Economy of Pakistan#labor force|workforce]] of over 1,800,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://propakistani.pk/2015/08/12/automotive-industrys-contribution-to-pakistan-infographic/|title=Automotive Industry's Contribution to Pakistan [Infographic]|website=propakistani.pk}}</ref> Currently there are over 3200 automotive manufacturing plants in the country, with an investment of {{PKRConvert|92|b}} producing 1.8 million motorcycles and 200,000 vehicles annually. Its contribution to the national exchequer is nearly {{PKRConvert|50|b}}. The sector, as a whole, provides employment to 3.5 million people and plays a pivotal role in promoting the growth of the vendor industry. Pakistan's auto market is considered among the smallest, but fastest growing in [[South Asia]]. Over 180,000 cars were sold in the fiscal year 2014\u201315, rising to 206,777 units fiscal year 2015\u201316.\n\n==Technology==\nPakistan has huge potential for the technology industry, which includes software development and electronics manufacturing. [[Pakistan Aeronautical Complex]] recently started the manufacturing of Tablet PCs, Ebook readers, and notebooks in collaboration with INNAVTEK of China. Software development also has a huge potential, which is being utilized as a result of numerous projects initiated by the [[Government of Pakistan]].\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Clifton Beach, Karachi - Pakistan.jpg|thumb|400px|Modern high-rises under construction at Clifton Beach, Karachi, Pakistan. Clifton area is fast becoming residential and commercial hub of Karachi.]]\nAfter the devastating [[2005 Kashmir earthquake]] Pakistan has instituted stricter building codes. The cost of construction in Pakistan will increase 30 to 50% due to implementation of a new building code which requires strengthening of structures to withstand earthquake of 8 to 8.5 magnitude. The demand for [[cement]] has increased due to reconstruction after the earthquake. The price of cement has increased by 50% and Pakistan government banned export of cement to lower the prices and the reconstruction costs.\n\n[[Dubai Ports World]], announced on June 1, 2006 that it will spend $10 billion to develop transport infrastructure and real estate in [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ameinfo.com/87639.html|title=Dubai World to set up projects worth USD10 billion across sectors in Pakistan - Dubai World<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> Dubai Ports World is also discussing the possibility of the company taking over operational management of [[Gwadar]] port in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C06%5C02%5Cstory_2-6-2006_pg1_4|title=Daily Times|website=Daily Times}}</ref>\n\n[[Emaar Properties]], announced on May 31, 2006 three real estate developments in the cities of [[Islamabad]] and [[Karachi]] in [[Pakistan]]. The projects, with a total investment of $2.4 billion, will include a series of master planned communities that will set new benchmarks in commercial, residential and retail property within Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emaar.com/MediaCenter/PressReleases/2006May31.asp|title=Emaar Technologies|website=www.emaar.com}}</ref>\n\nIn addition the conglomerate signed an unprecedented $43 billion deal to develop two island resorts - [[Bundal Island]] and [[Buddo Island]] - over the next decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/5387590.stm|title=Pakistan agrees $43bn development|date=28 September 2006|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued this sector at Rs.178,819 million in 2005 thus registering over 88% growth since 2000.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\"/>\n\n==Electricity, gas and water supply==\n{{See also|Electricity Sector in Pakistan}}\n\nPakistan has extensive energy resources, including fairly sizable [[natural gas]] reserves, some proven oil reserves, [[coal]] (Pakistan has the largest coal reserves in the world<ref name=\"coal\">[http://www.gsp.gov.pk/resources/seminars2.htm Coal, Granite, China Clay and other Resources of Thar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211143128/http://www.gsp.gov.pk/resources/seminars2.htm |date=2010-02-11 }}, ''Geological Survey of Pakistan'', URL accessed on April 2, 2006</ref>), and a large [[Hydroelectricity|hydropower]] potential. However, the exploitation of energy resources has been slow due to a shortage of capital and domestic political constraints. Domestic petroleum production totals only about half the country's oil needs, and the need to import oil has contributed to Pakistan's trade deficits and past shortages of foreign exchange.\n\nThe current government has announced that privatization in the oil and gas sector is a priority, as is the substitution of indigenous gas for imported oil, especially in the production of power. Pakistan is a world leader in the use of [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG) for personal automobiles.\n\nThe short-term national energy demand has expanded significantly since 2001 due to massive rise in sales of durable goods like refrigerators, washing machines, split air conditioners, ''et al.''.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/5338402.stm\n</ref>\nIn 2004, [[Access Group International]] announced plans to invest $1 billion over the next 5 years in [[solar cell]] manufacture and [[wind farm]]s. MOUs have been signed with [[Alternate Energy Development Board]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pakistantimes.net/2004/11/09/business1.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201085319/http://pakistantimes.net/2004/11/09/business1.htm |archive-date=2008-12-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In early 2005, the government approved a 25-year Energy Security Plan to boost electric capacity eightfold.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pakistantimes.net/2005/03/23/business4.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012130036/http://pakistantimes.net/2005/03/23/business4.htm |archive-date=2008-10-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian conglomerate [[Cathy Oil and Gas]] signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] in late 2006 to invest $5 billion in oil and gas exploration, development, production and commercialisation in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2006/09/26/top12.htm|title=Canadian firm to invest $5bn in oil and gas exploration|date=26 September 2006|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe World Bank estimates that it takes about 32 days only to get an electrical connection in Pakistan.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/>\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued this sector at Rs.215,662 million in 2005 thus registering over 62% growth since 2000.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Pakistan]]\n*[[International rankings of Pakistan]]\n*[[Science and technology in Pakistan]]\n*[[Fuel extraction in Pakistan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Economy of Pakistan}}\n{{Asia topic|Industry of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Industry Of Pakistan}}\n[[Category:Industry in Pakistan| ]]\n", "text_old": "Pakistan's industrial sector accounts for about 64% of GDP. Cotton textile production and apparel manufacturing are Pakistan's largest industries, accounting for about 65% of the merchandise exports and almost 40% of the employed labour force.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\">http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/IW3P/IB/2006/05/23/000012009_20060523095241/Rendered/PDF/354991PK0rev0pdf.pdf</ref> Cotton and cotton-based products account for 61% of export earnings of Pakistan. The consumption of cotton increased by 5.7% over the past five years while the economic growth rate was 7%. By 2010 the spinning capacity increased to 15 million spindles and textile exports hit $15.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Bank Archives |url=https://wits.worldbank.org/CountryProfile/en/Country/PAK/Year/2010/Summarytext |website=worldbank.org |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> Other major industries include cement, fertilizer, edible oil, sugar, steel, tobacco, chemicals, machinery and food processing.\n\nThe government is [[privatization|privatizing]] large-scale parastatal units, and the public sector accounts for a shrinking proportion of industrial output, while growth in overall industrial output (including the private sector) has accelerated. Government policies aim to diversify the country's industrial base and bolster export industries.\n\n==Mining and quarrying==\nThe country has immense reserves of various minerals and natural resources.  Important minerals found in Pakistan are [[gypsum]], [[limestone]], [[chromite]]s, [[iron ore]], rock salt, [[silver]], [[gold]], precious stones, [[gemstone|gem]]s, marble, [[copper]], [[coal]], [[graphite]], [[sulphur]], fire clay, [[silica]]. The salt range in Punjab Province has one of the largest deposit of pure salt founded in the world. [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]] province is a mineral-rich area having substantial mineral, oil and gas reserves which have not been exploited to their full capacity or fully explored, recent government policies have begun to develop this region of the country and to tap into the immense resources found there. The province has significant quantities of copper, chromite and iron, and pockets of antimony and zinc in the south and gold in the far west. Natural gas was discovered near Sui in 1952, and the province has been gradually developing its oil and gas projects over the past fifty years.<ref name=\"minerals\">{{cite web|url=http://www.himalmag.com/2002/july/profile_2.htm|title=Himala South Asian, Pakistan Edition|publisher=|access-date=2008-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021155040/http://himalmag.com/2002/july/profile_2.htm|archive-date=2007-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMajor reserves of copper and gold in Balochistan's [[Reko Diq]] area have been discovered in early 2006. The Reko Diq mining area has proven estimated reserves of 2 billion tons of copper and 20 million ounces of gold. According to the current market price, the value of the deposits has been estimated at about $65 billion, which would generate thousands of jobs.\n\nThe discovery has ranked Rekodiq among the world's top seven copper reserves. The Rekodiq project is estimated to produce 200,000 tons of copper and 400,000 ounces of gold per year, at an estimated value of $1.25 billion at current market prices. The copper and gold are currently traded at about $5,000 per ton and $600 per ounce respectively in the international market.<ref>http://www.pakpositive.com/common/clicks/out2.php?pakpositive=%3A%2F%2Fwww.dawn.com%2F2006%2F04%2F14%2Ftop8.htm\n</ref>\n[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Province]] accounts for at least 78% of the marble production in Pakistan. Pakistan is home to some of the most finest and purest grades of marble, granite and slate found in the world.  Much of the grades A Marble that is exported out of European countries like Italy actually have their origins in Pakistan which previously lacked fine polishing and processing machinery.  The Government has taken steps to invest in this crucial sector with the recent establishment of a ''Marble City'' within Balochistan.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/>69\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued this sector at Rs.211,851 million in 2005 thus registering over 99% growth since 2000.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">https://web.archive.org/web/20070619224443/http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/fbs/statistics/national_accounts/table4.pdf</ref>\n\n==Fuel extraction industry==\n{{Main|Fuel extraction in Pakistan}}\nPakistan's first [[oil field]] was discovered in the late 1952 in Balochistan near a giant [[gas field]] at suo [[Sui, Balochistan|Sui]] in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]]. The [[Toot oilfield]] was discovered in the early 1960s Islamabad in the Punjab. Production has steadily increased since then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakpositive.com/2005/01/06/canadian-firm-to-develop-pakistan-oilfield/|title=Canadian Firm to Develop Pakistan Oilfield - PakPositive|website=www.pakpositive.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Pakistan]]'s first gas field was the giant [[gas field]] at Sui in Balochistan which was discovered in the late 1952.\n<ref>https://archive.today/20070528143233/http://www.pakistan.gov.pk/divisions/ContentInfo.jsp?DivID=49&cPath=768_867&ContentID=5217\n</ref>\nPakistan is also a major producer of  Bituminous coal, Sub-bituminous coal and Lignite. Coal mining started in the British colonial era and has continued to be used by Pakistani industries after independence in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://islamabad.usembassy.gov/pakistan/h07091701.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102175405/http://islamabad.usembassy.gov/pakistan/h07091701.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 November 2007|title=USTDA Grant To Support Integrated Coal Mining, Power Generation Project In Pakistan - U.S. Embassy Islamabad Pakistan|date=2 November 2007|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakistaneconomist.com/database2/cover/c2001-41.asp|title=Page not found - Pakistan & Gulf Economist|author=|date=|website=Pakistan & Gulf Economist}}</ref>\n\nPakistan produced about 45 tonnes of Uranium in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/inf23.html|title=World Uranium Mining 2016 - World Nuclear Association|website=www.world-nuclear.org}}</ref>\n\n==Manufacturing==\nIn FY 2002-03, real growth in manufacturing was 7.7%. In the twelve months ending 30 June 2004, large-scale manufacturing grew by more than 18% compared to the previous twelve-month period. The textile and garment industry's share in the economy along with its contribution to exports, employment, foreign-exchange earnings, investment and value added make it Pakistan's single largest manufacturing sector. The industry comprises 453 textile mills: 50 integrated units; and 403 spinning units, with 9.33 million spindles and 148,000 rotors, The capacity utilization was 83% for spindles and 47% for rotors during 2003.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/>\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued large-scale manufacturing at Rs.981,518 million in 2005 thus registering over 138% growth since 2000 <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/fbs/statistics/national_accounts/table4.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070619224443/http://www.statpak.gov.pk/depts/fbs/statistics/national_accounts/table4.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 June 2007|title=Wayback Machine|date=19 June 2007|publisher=}}</ref> while small-scale manufacturing was valued at Rs.356,835 million in 2005 thus registering over 80% growth since 2000.\n\n==Automotive Industry==\n'''[[Automotive industry in Pakistan|Pakistan's automotive industry]]''' is the one of the fastest growing industries of the country, accounting for 4% of Pakistan's GDP and employing a [[Economy of Pakistan#labor force|workforce]] of over 1,800,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://propakistani.pk/2015/08/12/automotive-industrys-contribution-to-pakistan-infographic/|title=Automotive Industry's Contribution to Pakistan [Infographic]|website=propakistani.pk}}</ref> Currently there are over 3200 automotive manufacturing plants in the country, with an investment of {{PKRConvert|92|b}} producing 1.8 million motorcycles and 200,000 vehicles annually. Its contribution to the national exchequer is nearly {{PKRConvert|50|b}}. The sector, as a whole, provides employment to 3.5 million people and plays a pivotal role in promoting the growth of the vendor industry. Pakistan's auto market is considered among the smallest, but fastest growing in [[South Asia]]. Over 180,000 cars were sold in the fiscal year 2014-15, rising to 206,777 units fiscal year 2015-16.\n\n==Technology==\nPakistan has huge potential for the technology industry, which includes software development and electronics manufacturing. [[Pakistan Aeronautical Complex]] recently started the manufacturing of Tablet PCs, Ebook readers, and notebooks in collaboration with INNAVTEK of China. Software development also has a huge potential, which is being utilized as a result of numerous projects initiated by the [[Government of Pakistan]].\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Clifton Beach, Karachi - Pakistan.jpg|thumb|400px|Modern high-rises under construction at Clifton Beach, Karachi, Pakistan. Clifton area is fast becoming residential and commercial hub of Karachi.]]\nAfter the devastating [[2005 Kashmir earthquake]] Pakistan has instituted stricter building codes. The cost of construction in Pakistan will increase 30 to 50% due to implementation of a new building code which requires strengthening of structures to withstand earthquake of 8 to 8.5 magnitude. The demand for [[cement]] has increased due to reconstruction after the earthquake. The price of cement has increased by 50% and Pakistan government banned export of cement to lower the prices and the reconstruction costs.\n\n[[Dubai Ports World]], announced on June 1, 2006 that it will spend $10 billion to develop transport infrastructure and real estate in [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ameinfo.com/87639.html|title=Dubai World to set up projects worth USD10 billion across sectors in Pakistan - Dubai World<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> Dubai Ports World is also discussing the possibility of the company taking over operational management of [[Gwadar]] port in [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C06%5C02%5Cstory_2-6-2006_pg1_4|title=Daily Times|website=Daily Times}}</ref>\n\n[[Emaar Properties]], announced on May 31, 2006 three real estate developments in the cities of [[Islamabad]] and [[Karachi]] in [[Pakistan]]. The projects, with a total investment of $2.4 billion, will include a series of master planned communities that will set new benchmarks in commercial, residential and retail property within Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emaar.com/MediaCenter/PressReleases/2006May31.asp|title=Emaar Technologies|website=www.emaar.com}}</ref>\n\nIn addition the conglomerate signed an unprecedented $43 billion deal to develop two island resorts - [[Bundal Island]] and [[Buddo Island]] - over the next decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/5387590.stm|title=Pakistan agrees $43bn development|date=28 September 2006|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued this sector at Rs.178,819 million in 2005 thus registering over 88% growth since 2000.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\"/>\n\n==Electricity, gas and water supply==\n{{See also|Electricity Sector in Pakistan}}\n\nPakistan has extensive energy resources, including fairly sizable [[natural gas]] reserves, some proven oil reserves, [[coal]] (Pakistan has the largest coal reserves in the world<ref name=\"coal\">[http://www.gsp.gov.pk/resources/seminars2.htm Coal, Granite, China Clay and other Resources of Thar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211143128/http://www.gsp.gov.pk/resources/seminars2.htm |date=2010-02-11 }}, ''Geological Survey of Pakistan'', URL accessed on April 2, 2006</ref>), and a large [[Hydroelectricity|hydropower]] potential. However, the exploitation of energy resources has been slow due to a shortage of capital and domestic political constraints. Domestic petroleum production totals only about half the country's oil needs, and the need to import oil has contributed to Pakistan's trade deficits and past shortages of foreign exchange.\n\nThe current government has announced that privatization in the oil and gas sector is a priority, as is the substitution of indigenous gas for imported oil, especially in the production of power. Pakistan is a world leader in the use of [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG) for personal automobiles.\n\nThe short-term national energy demand has expanded significantly since 2001 due to massive rise in sales of durable goods like refrigerators, washing machines, split air conditioners, ''et al.''.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/5338402.stm\n</ref>\nIn 2004, [[Access Group International]] announced plans to invest $1 billion over the next 5 years in [[solar cell]] manufacture and [[wind farm]]s. MOUs have been signed with [[Alternate Energy Development Board]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pakistantimes.net/2004/11/09/business1.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201085319/http://pakistantimes.net/2004/11/09/business1.htm |archive-date=2008-12-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In early 2005, the government approved a 25-year Energy Security Plan to boost electric capacity eightfold.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pakistantimes.net/2005/03/23/business4.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012130036/http://pakistantimes.net/2005/03/23/business4.htm |archive-date=2008-10-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian conglomerate [[Cathy Oil and Gas]] signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] in late 2006 to invest $5 billion in oil and gas exploration, development, production and commercialisation in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2006/09/26/top12.htm|title=Canadian firm to invest $5bn in oil and gas exploration|date=26 September 2006|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe World Bank estimates that it takes about 32 days only to get an electrical connection in Pakistan.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/>\n\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Statistics]] provisionally valued this sector at Rs.215,662 million in 2005 thus registering over 62% growth since 2000.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Pakistan]]\n*[[International rankings of Pakistan]]\n*[[Science and technology in Pakistan]]\n*[[Fuel extraction in Pakistan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Economy of Pakistan}}\n{{Asia topic|Industry of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Industry Of Pakistan}}\n[[Category:Industry in Pakistan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2002-03 \u2192 2002\u201303 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industry_of_Pakistan"}
{"title_page": "Carl Theodor Dreyer", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish film director}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Carl Theodor Dreyer\n| image = Carl Theodor Dreyer (1965) by Erling Mandelmann.jpg\n| caption = Dreyer in 1965\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1889|2|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|1968|3|20|1889|2|3}}\n| death_place = Copenhagen, Denmark\n| occupation = Film director\n| years_active = 1919\u201368\n| spouse = {{marriage|Ebba Larsen|1911}} (d.1977)\n| children = Gunni<br />Erik\n| awards = '''[[Golden Lion]]''' at the 1955 [[Venice Film Festival]] for<br /> ''[[Ordet]]'' \n}}\n'''Carl Theodor Dreyer''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0a\u02c0l \u02c8ts\u02b0e\u02d0ot\u0252 \u02c8t\u0281aj\u02c0\u0250|lang}}; 3 February 1889 \u2013 20 March 1968), commonly known as '''Carl Th. Dreyer''',<ref>[http://english.carlthdreyer.dk The Carl Th. Dreyer website] Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> was a Danish film director. He is regarded by many critics and filmmakers as one of the greatest directors in cinema.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://w.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm |title=The 1,000 Greatest Films (Top 250 Directors) |publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They |accessdate=December 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202170655/http://w.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm |archive-date=2 December 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/29/carldreyer.html [[Bright Lights Film Journal]] review of Day of Wrath, Order and Gertrud]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kamera.co.uk/article.php/173|title=kamera.co.uk - feature item - Carl Dreyer - Antonio Pasolini|website=www.kamera.co.uk|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/carl-theodor-dreyer-p88264|title=Carl Theodor Dreyer {{!}} Biography, Movie Highlights and Photos {{!}} AllMovie|website=AllMovie|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref><ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19970216/REVIEWS08/401010350/1023 The Passion of Joan of Arc review by [[Roger Ebert]]]</ref> His best known films include ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]'' (1928), ''[[Vampyr]]'' (1932), ''[[Day of Wrath]]'' (1943), ''[[Ordet]]'' (1955), and ''[[Gertrud (film)|Gertrud]]'' (1964).\n\n==Life==\nDreyer was born [[illegitimate]] in Copenhagen, Denmark. His birth mother was an unmarried [[Scania]]n maid named Josefine Bernhardine Nilsson, and he was put up for adoption by his birth father, Jens Christian Torp, a married Danish farmer living in Sweden who was his mother's employer. He spent the first two years of his life in orphanages until his adoption by a typographer named Carl Theodor Dreyer, and his wife, Inger Marie (n\u00e9e Olsen). He was named after his adoptive father, but in accordance with Danish practice, there is no \"Senior\" or \"Junior\" added to their names to distinguish them from each other.\n\nHis adoptive parents were emotionally distant and his childhood was largely unhappy. He later recalled that his parents \"constantly let me know that I should be grateful for the food I was given and that I strictly had no claim on anything, since my mother got out of paying by lying down to die.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://english.carlthdreyer.dk/AboutDreyer/Biography/Biography---extended.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204004614/http://english.carlthdreyer.dk/AboutDreyer/Biography/Biography---extended.aspx |archive-date=4 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> But he was a highly intelligent school student, who left home and formal education at the age of sixteen. He dissociated himself from his adoptive family, but their teachings were to influence the themes of many of his films.\n\nDreyer was ideologically conservative. According to [[David Bordwell]], \"As a youth he belonged to the Social Liberal party, a conservative group radical only in their opposition to military expenditures...'Even when I was with ''[[Ekstra Bladet|Ekstrabladet]]'',' Dreyer recalled, 'I was conservative...I don't believe in revolutions. They have, as a rule, the tedious quality of pulling development back. I believe more in evolution, in the small advances.'\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Films of Carl Theodor Dreyer|last=Bordwell|first=David|publisher=University of California Press|year=1983|page=191}}</ref>\n\nDreyer died of pneumonia in Copenhagen at age 79. The documentary ''[[Carl Th. Dreyer: My Metier]]'' contains reminiscences from those who knew him.\n\n==Career==\nAs a young man, Dreyer worked as a journalist, but he eventually joined the film industry as a writer of title cards for silent films and subsequently of screenplays. He was initially hired by [[Nordisk Film]] in 1913.\n\nHis first attempts at film direction had limited success, and he left Denmark to work in the French film industry. While living in France he met [[Jean Cocteau]], [[Jean Hugo]] and other members of the French artistic scene and in 1928 he made his first classic film, ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]''. Working from the transcripts of Joan's trial, he created a masterpiece of emotion that drew equally on realism and expressionism. Dreyer used private finance from Baron [[Nicolas de Gunzburg]] to make his next film as the Danish film industry was in financial ruin. ''[[Vampyr]]'' (1932) is a surreal meditation on fear. Logic gave way to mood and atmosphere in this story of a man protecting two sisters from a vampire. The movie contains many indelible images, such as the hero, played by de Gunzburg (under the screen name Julian West), dreaming of his own burial and the animal blood lust on the face of one of the sisters as she suffers under the vampire's spell. The film was shot mostly silent but with sparse, cryptic dialogue in three separate versions \u2013 English, French and German.\n\nBoth films were box office failures, and Dreyer did not make another movie until 1943. Denmark was by now under Nazi occupation, and his ''[[Day of Wrath]]'' had as its theme the paranoia surrounding witch hunts in the seventeenth century in a strongly [[Theocracy|theocratic]] culture. With this work, Dreyer established the style that would mark his sound films: careful compositions, stark monochrome cinematography, and very long takes. In the more than a decade before his next full-length feature film, Dreyer made two documentaries. In 1955, he made ''[[Ordet]]'' (''The Word'') based on the play of the same name by [[Kaj Munk]]. The film combines a love story with a conflict of faith. Dreyer's last film was 1964's ''[[Gertrud (film)|Gertrud]]''. Although seen by some as a lesser film than its predecessors, it is a fitting close to Dreyer's career, as it deals with a woman who, through the tribulations of her life, never expresses regret for her choices.\n\nThe great, never finished project of Dreyer's career was a film about Jesus. Though a manuscript was written (published 1968) the unstable economic conditions and Dreyer's own demands of realism together with his switching engagement let it remain a dream.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Feature films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"5%\"|Year\n!width=\"20%\"|English title\n!width=\"25%\"|Original title\n!width=\"10%\"|Production country\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''The President''\n| ''[[Pr\u00e6sidenten]]''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the novel by [[Karl Emil Franzos]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1920\n| ''[[The Parson's Widow]]''\n| ''Pr\u00e4st\u00e4nkan''\n| Sweden\n| Based on the story \"Prestekonen\" by [[Kristofer Janson]].\n|-\n| 1921\n| ''[[Leaves from Satan's Book]]''\n| ''Blade af Satans bog''\n| Denmark\n| Loosely based on ''[[The Sorrows of Satan]]''.\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1922\n| ''[[Die Gezeichneten (1922 film)|Love One Another]]''\n| ''Die Gezeichneten''\n| Germany\n| Based on the novel by [[Aage Madelung]], this film is extremely rare (only 4 prints survive in archives).\n|-\n| 1922\n| ''Once Upon a Time''\n| ''Der var engang''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play by [[Holger Drachmann]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1924\n| ''[[Michael (1924 film)|Michael]]''\n| ''Mika\u00ebl''\n| Germany\n| Based on the novel ''Mika\u00ebl'' (1904) by [[Herman Bang]].\n|-\n| 1925\n| ''[[Master of the House]]'' (aka ''Thou Shalt Honor Thy Wife'')\n| ''Du skal \u00e6re din hustru''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play by [[Svend Rindom]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1926\n| ''[[The Bride of Glomdal]]''\n| ''Glomdalsbruden''\n| Norway\n| Based on the novel by [[Jacob Breda Bull]].\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]''\n| ''La Passion de Jeanne d'Arc (Jeanne d'Arc lidelse og d\u00f8d) ''\n| France\n| Co-written with [[Joseph Delteil]], author of the novel ''Jeanne d'Arc'' (1925, [[Prix Femina]]). Named the most influential film of all time by the curators of the 2010 [[Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Copenhagen Post\">{{cite news|title=Dreyer film voted most influential |url=http://www.cphpost.dk/culture/culture/122-culture/50054-danish-directors-film-voted-most-influential.html|accessdate=26 September 2010|newspaper=[[Copenhagen Post]]|date=22 September 2010}}</ref>\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1932\n| ''[[Vampyr]]''\n| ''Vampyr \u2013 Der Traum des Allan Grey''\n| France/Germany\n| Based on the novella ''[[Carmilla]]'' (1872) by [[Sheridan Le Fanu|J. Sheridan Le Fanu]].\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''[[Day of Wrath]]''\n| ''Vredens Dag''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play ''[[Anne Pedersdotter (play)|Anne Pedersdotter]]'' by [[Hans Wiers-Jenssen]]; hymns by Paul La Cour.\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1945\n| ''Two People''\n| ''Tv\u00e5 m\u00e4nniskor''\n| Sweden\n| Based on the play \"Attentat\" by W.O. Somin. Made in Nazi-related exile in Sweden, the film was disowned by Dreyer and withdrawn from distribution.\n|-\n| 1955\n| ''[[Ordet|The Word]]''\n| ''Ordet''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play by [[Kaj Munk]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1964\n| ''[[Gertrud (film)|Gertrud]]''\n| ''Gertrud''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the [[Gertrud (play)|play]] by [[Hjalmar S\u00f6derberg]].\n|}\n\n===Short films===\n*''Good Mothers'' (''M\u00f8drehj\u00e6lpen'', 12 min, 1942)\n*''Water from the Land'' (''Vandet p\u00e5 landet'', 1946)\n*''The Struggle Against Cancer'' (''Kampen mod kr\u00e6ften'', 15 min, 1947)\n*''The Danish Village Church'' (''Landsbykirken'', 14 min, 1947)\n*''They Caught the Ferry'' (''De n\u00e5ede f\u00e6rgen'', 11 min, 1948)\n*''Thorvaldsen'' (10 min, 1949)\n*''The [[Storstrom Bridge]]'' (''Storstr\u00f8msbroen'', 7 min, 1950)\n*''The Castle Within the Castle'' (''Et Slot i et slot'', 1955)\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Main|Carl Theodor Dreyer bibliography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://english.carlthdreyer.dk Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0003433|name=Carl Theodor Dreyer}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070202184213/http://www.carldreyer.com/ CarlDreyer.com] (archived)\n* [http://www.carldreyer.com/resources/dreyerbypaulmoor51.htm In-depth article from 1951 on 'The Tyrannical Dane']\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=1460 Bibliography]\n* [http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/131-thoughts-on-my-metier Thoughts on My M\u00e9tier by Carl Theodor Dreyer]\n* [http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/226-carl-th-dreyer Carl Th. Dreyer by Armond White]\n\n{{Carl Theodor Dreyer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dreyer, Carl Theodor}}\n[[Category:Carl Theodor Dreyer| ]]\n[[Category:Danish screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:Silent film directors]]\n[[Category:Danish film directors]]\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish adoptees]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Directors of Golden Lion winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish film director}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Carl Theodor Dreyer\n| image = Carl Theodor Dreyer (1965) by Erling Mandelmann.jpg\n| caption = Dreyer in 1965\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1889|2|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|1968|3|20|1889|2|3}}\n| death_place = Copenhagen, Denmark\n| occupation = Film director\n| years_active = 1919\u201368\n| spouse = {{marriage|Ebba Larsen|1911}} (d.1977)\n| children = Gunni<br />Erik\n| awards = '''[[Golden Lion]]''' at the 1955 [[Venice Film Festival]] for<br /> ''[[Ordet]]'' \n}}\n'''Carl Theodor Dreyer''' ({{IPA-da|k\u02b0al ts\u02b0e\u02d0oto\u0250\u032f \u02c8t\u0281aj\u02c0\u0250|lang}}; 3 February 1889 \u2013 20 March 1968), commonly known as '''Carl Th. Dreyer''',<ref>[http://english.carlthdreyer.dk The Carl Th. Dreyer website] Retrieved 12 March 2013</ref> was a Danish film director. He is regarded by many critics and filmmakers as one of the greatest directors in cinema.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://w.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm |title=The 1,000 Greatest Films (Top 250 Directors) |publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They |accessdate=December 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202170655/http://w.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm |archive-date=2 December 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/29/carldreyer.html [[Bright Lights Film Journal]] review of Day of Wrath, Order and Gertrud]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kamera.co.uk/article.php/173|title=kamera.co.uk - feature item - Carl Dreyer - Antonio Pasolini|website=www.kamera.co.uk|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/carl-theodor-dreyer-p88264|title=Carl Theodor Dreyer {{!}} Biography, Movie Highlights and Photos {{!}} AllMovie|website=AllMovie|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref><ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19970216/REVIEWS08/401010350/1023 The Passion of Joan of Arc review by [[Roger Ebert]]]</ref> His best known films include ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]'' (1928), ''[[Vampyr]]'' (1932), ''[[Day of Wrath]]'' (1943), ''[[Ordet]]'' (1955), and ''[[Gertrud (film)|Gertrud]]'' (1964).\n\n==Life==\nDreyer was born [[illegitimate]] in Copenhagen, Denmark. His birth mother was an unmarried [[Scania]]n maid named Josefine Bernhardine Nilsson, and he was put up for adoption by his birth father, Jens Christian Torp, a married Danish farmer living in Sweden who was his mother's employer. He spent the first two years of his life in orphanages until his adoption by a typographer named Carl Theodor Dreyer, and his wife, Inger Marie (n\u00e9e Olsen). He was named after his adoptive father, but in accordance with Danish practice, there is no \"Senior\" or \"Junior\" added to their names to distinguish them from each other.\n\nHis adoptive parents were emotionally distant and his childhood was largely unhappy. He later recalled that his parents \"constantly let me know that I should be grateful for the food I was given and that I strictly had no claim on anything, since my mother got out of paying by lying down to die.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://english.carlthdreyer.dk/AboutDreyer/Biography/Biography---extended.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204004614/http://english.carlthdreyer.dk/AboutDreyer/Biography/Biography---extended.aspx |archive-date=4 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> But he was a highly intelligent school student, who left home and formal education at the age of sixteen. He dissociated himself from his adoptive family, but their teachings were to influence the themes of many of his films.\n\nDreyer was ideologically conservative. According to [[David Bordwell]], \"As a youth he belonged to the Social Liberal party, a conservative group radical only in their opposition to military expenditures...'Even when I was with ''[[Ekstra Bladet|Ekstrabladet]]'',' Dreyer recalled, 'I was conservative...I don't believe in revolutions. They have, as a rule, the tedious quality of pulling development back. I believe more in evolution, in the small advances.'\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Films of Carl Theodor Dreyer|last=Bordwell|first=David|publisher=University of California Press|year=1983|page=191}}</ref>\n\nDreyer died of pneumonia in Copenhagen at age 79. The documentary ''[[Carl Th. Dreyer: My Metier]]'' contains reminiscences from those who knew him.\n\n==Career==\nAs a young man, Dreyer worked as a journalist, but he eventually joined the film industry as a writer of title cards for silent films and subsequently of screenplays. He was initially hired by [[Nordisk Film]] in 1913.\n\nHis first attempts at film direction had limited success, and he left Denmark to work in the French film industry. While living in France he met [[Jean Cocteau]], [[Jean Hugo]] and other members of the French artistic scene and in 1928 he made his first classic film, ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]''. Working from the transcripts of Joan's trial, he created a masterpiece of emotion that drew equally on realism and expressionism. Dreyer used private finance from Baron [[Nicolas de Gunzburg]] to make his next film as the Danish film industry was in financial ruin. ''[[Vampyr]]'' (1932) is a surreal meditation on fear. Logic gave way to mood and atmosphere in this story of a man protecting two sisters from a vampire. The movie contains many indelible images, such as the hero, played by de Gunzburg (under the screen name Julian West), dreaming of his own burial and the animal blood lust on the face of one of the sisters as she suffers under the vampire's spell. The film was shot mostly silent but with sparse, cryptic dialogue in three separate versions \u2013 English, French and German.\n\nBoth films were box office failures, and Dreyer did not make another movie until 1943. Denmark was by now under Nazi occupation, and his ''[[Day of Wrath]]'' had as its theme the paranoia surrounding witch hunts in the seventeenth century in a strongly [[Theocracy|theocratic]] culture. With this work, Dreyer established the style that would mark his sound films: careful compositions, stark monochrome cinematography, and very long takes. In the more than a decade before his next full-length feature film, Dreyer made two documentaries. In 1955, he made ''[[Ordet]]'' (''The Word'') based on the play of the same name by [[Kaj Munk]]. The film combines a love story with a conflict of faith. Dreyer's last film was 1964's ''[[Gertrud (film)|Gertrud]]''. Although seen by some as a lesser film than its predecessors, it is a fitting close to Dreyer's career, as it deals with a woman who, through the tribulations of her life, never expresses regret for her choices.\n\nThe great, never finished project of Dreyer's career was a film about Jesus. Though a manuscript was written (published 1968) the unstable economic conditions and Dreyer's own demands of realism together with his switching engagement let it remain a dream.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Feature films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"5%\"|Year\n!width=\"20%\"|English title\n!width=\"25%\"|Original title\n!width=\"10%\"|Production country\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1919\n| ''The President''\n| ''[[Pr\u00e6sidenten]]''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the novel by [[Karl Emil Franzos]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1920\n| ''[[The Parson's Widow]]''\n| ''Pr\u00e4st\u00e4nkan''\n| Sweden\n| Based on the story \"Prestekonen\" by [[Kristofer Janson]].\n|-\n| 1921\n| ''[[Leaves from Satan's Book]]''\n| ''Blade af Satans bog''\n| Denmark\n| Loosely based on ''[[The Sorrows of Satan]]''.\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1922\n| ''[[Die Gezeichneten (1922 film)|Love One Another]]''\n| ''Die Gezeichneten''\n| Germany\n| Based on the novel by [[Aage Madelung]], this film is extremely rare (only 4 prints survive in archives).\n|-\n| 1922\n| ''Once Upon a Time''\n| ''Der var engang''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play by [[Holger Drachmann]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1924\n| ''[[Michael (1924 film)|Michael]]''\n| ''Mika\u00ebl''\n| Germany\n| Based on the novel ''Mika\u00ebl'' (1904) by [[Herman Bang]].\n|-\n| 1925\n| ''[[Master of the House]]'' (aka ''Thou Shalt Honor Thy Wife'')\n| ''Du skal \u00e6re din hustru''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play by [[Svend Rindom]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1926\n| ''[[The Bride of Glomdal]]''\n| ''Glomdalsbruden''\n| Norway\n| Based on the novel by [[Jacob Breda Bull]].\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]''\n| ''La Passion de Jeanne d'Arc (Jeanne d'Arc lidelse og d\u00f8d) ''\n| France\n| Co-written with [[Joseph Delteil]], author of the novel ''Jeanne d'Arc'' (1925, [[Prix Femina]]). Named the most influential film of all time by the curators of the 2010 [[Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Copenhagen Post\">{{cite news|title=Dreyer film voted most influential |url=http://www.cphpost.dk/culture/culture/122-culture/50054-danish-directors-film-voted-most-influential.html|accessdate=26 September 2010|newspaper=[[Copenhagen Post]]|date=22 September 2010}}</ref>\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1932\n| ''[[Vampyr]]''\n| ''Vampyr \u2013 Der Traum des Allan Grey''\n| France/Germany\n| Based on the novella ''[[Carmilla]]'' (1872) by [[Sheridan Le Fanu|J. Sheridan Le Fanu]].\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''[[Day of Wrath]]''\n| ''Vredens Dag''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play ''[[Anne Pedersdotter (play)|Anne Pedersdotter]]'' by [[Hans Wiers-Jenssen]]; hymns by Paul La Cour.\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1945\n| ''Two People''\n| ''Tv\u00e5 m\u00e4nniskor''\n| Sweden\n| Based on the play \"Attentat\" by W.O. Somin. Made in Nazi-related exile in Sweden, the film was disowned by Dreyer and withdrawn from distribution.\n|-\n| 1955\n| ''[[Ordet|The Word]]''\n| ''Ordet''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the play by [[Kaj Munk]].\n|-style=background:#efefef;\n| 1964\n| ''[[Gertrud (film)|Gertrud]]''\n| ''Gertrud''\n| Denmark\n| Based on the [[Gertrud (play)|play]] by [[Hjalmar S\u00f6derberg]].\n|}\n\n===Short films===\n*''Good Mothers'' (''M\u00f8drehj\u00e6lpen'', 12 min, 1942)\n*''Water from the Land'' (''Vandet p\u00e5 landet'', 1946)\n*''The Struggle Against Cancer'' (''Kampen mod kr\u00e6ften'', 15 min, 1947)\n*''The Danish Village Church'' (''Landsbykirken'', 14 min, 1947)\n*''They Caught the Ferry'' (''De n\u00e5ede f\u00e6rgen'', 11 min, 1948)\n*''Thorvaldsen'' (10 min, 1949)\n*''The [[Storstrom Bridge]]'' (''Storstr\u00f8msbroen'', 7 min, 1950)\n*''The Castle Within the Castle'' (''Et Slot i et slot'', 1955)\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Main|Carl Theodor Dreyer bibliography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://english.carlthdreyer.dk Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0003433|name=Carl Theodor Dreyer}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070202184213/http://www.carldreyer.com/ CarlDreyer.com] (archived)\n* [http://www.carldreyer.com/resources/dreyerbypaulmoor51.htm In-depth article from 1951 on 'The Tyrannical Dane']\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=1460 Bibliography]\n* [http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/131-thoughts-on-my-metier Thoughts on My M\u00e9tier by Carl Theodor Dreyer]\n* [http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/226-carl-th-dreyer Carl Th. Dreyer by Armond White]\n\n{{Carl Theodor Dreyer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dreyer, Carl Theodor}}\n[[Category:Carl Theodor Dreyer| ]]\n[[Category:Danish screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:Silent film directors]]\n[[Category:Danish film directors]]\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish adoptees]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Directors of Golden Lion winners]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Theodor_Dreyer"}
{"title_page": "The Quality of Nationality Index", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title      = no\n| name              = The Quality of Nationality Index\n| image             = Quality of Nationality Index logo.jpg\n| alt               = \n| caption           = The Quality of Nationality Index Logo 2017\n| author            = [[Christian K\u00e4lin|Dr. Christian H. K\u00e4lin]] & Prof. Dr. Dimitry Kochenov\n| audio_read_by     = \n| title_orig        = \n| orig_lang_code    = \n| title_working     = \n| translator        = \n| illustrator       = \n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = \n| language          = English\n| series            = \n| release_number    = 2017\n| subject           = \n| genre             = \n| set_in            = \n| publisher         = Henley & Partners\n| publisher2        = \n| pub_date          = \n| english_pub_date  = \n| published         = \n| media_type        = \n| pages             = \n| awards            = \n| isbn              = \n| isbn_note         = \n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource        = \n| notes             = \n| exclude_cover     = \n| website           = https://www.nationalityindex.com/\n}}\n\n'''The Quality of Nationality Index''' ('''QNI''') ranks the quality of nationalities based on internal and external factors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2017/09/13/germany-tops-quality-of-nationality-index.html |title=Germany Tops Quality of Nationality Index |date= 2017-09-13 |website=cnbc.com |access-date= 2018-08-16}}</ref> Each nationality receives an aggregated score based on their economic strength, human development, ease of travel, political stability and overseas employment opportunities for their citizens. The data is collected from various sources with quantifiable data.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kochenov|first1=Dimitry|last2=Lindeboom|first2=Justin|date=October 2017|title=Empirical Assessment of the Quality of Nationalities: The Quality of Nationality Index (QNI)|journal=European Journal of Comparative Law and Governance|volume=4|issue=4|pages=314\u2013336|doi=10.1163/22134514-00404007|ssrn=3053624}}</ref> The QNI was created by Dimitry Kochenov, an expert in citizenship, nationality and immigration law and constitutional law of the European Union at the [[University of Groningen]] and [[Christian K\u00e4lin]], chairman of [[Henley & Partners]].\n\n== Significance ==\nThe phenomenon of being a native of any country has also been described as \u2018a birthright lottery\u2019 by Professor of Law, Political Science, and Global Affairs [[Ayelet Shachar]] at the [[University of Toronto]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rorotoko.com/interview/20090828_shachar_ayelet_birthright_lottery_citizenship_global_inequality/?page=2 |title=Birthright is a Lottery |publisher=rorotoko.com |date=2018-08-17 |accessdate=2018-08-17}}</ref> At the same time, the QNI shows that nationalities diverge greatly in their practical value which often does not run parallel with the characteristics of the countries with which nationalities are associated, such as the economic power or the level of human development of the countries. Applying the methodology of the QNI, some economically strong countries have relatively unattractive nationalities. For example, the nationality of India shares the 106th place with the nationality of Senegal (2017 data). By contrast, some small countries have nationalities of larger value, such as those of Lithuania and Romania, which are ranked 22nd and 25th respectively in the QNI 2017.\n\nThe QNI is frequently cited in media such as ''[[Forbes]]'', [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]], ''[[National Enquirer|The Enquirer]]'' and ''[[Business Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/passport/2018/05/04/the-worlds-top-nationalities-a-ski-resort-with-a-slope-on-its-roof-and-more/#50564ae5483e |title=The World's Top Nationalities  |work=Forbes |date=2018-08-17 |accessdate=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2018-buying-citizenship/ |title=Where the Super-Rich go to buy their second Passport |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2018-08-17 |accessdate=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/984809/worlds-best-nationalities-for-2017-revealed-ph-ranks-125th |title=World's best Nationalities for 2017 revealed |publisher=The Enquirer |date=2018-08-17 |accessdate=2018-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/international/where-the-super-rich-go-to-buy-their-second-passport-118072100766_1.html |title=Looking for another Passport \u2013 Here are the most sought after countries |publisher=Business Standard |date=2018-08-17 |accessdate=2018-08-17}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Quality of Nationality Index results geographic distribution.jpg|thumb|QNI World Map]]\n\n== Methodology ==\nThe QNI takes a quantitative approach to determine the value of a nationality based on seven parameters, comprising both internal value (40%) and external value (60%). Three parameters reflect the internal value of a nationality: human development (15%), economic strength (15%), and peace and stability (10%). Four parameters reflect the external value of a nationality: diversity of travel freedom (15%), weight of travel freedom (15%), diversity of settlement freedom (15%), and weight of settlement freedom (15%).<ref>{{cite news|url=|title=Methodology of the QNI|last=Kochenov|first=Dimitry|work=The Quality of Nationality Index|accessdate=|publisher=Ideos Publishing|last2=Lindeboom|first2=Justin|year=2018|edition= 3rd|orig-year=2018}}</ref>\n\nVirtually all nationalities of the world as well as EU citizenship are included in the ranking. Not included are [[Camouflage passport|fantasy passports]] and nationalities of non-recognized states such as [[Abkhazia]], [[South Ossetia|South-Ossetia]], and [[Somaliland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Quality of Nationality Index|last=Lindeboom|first=Justin|publisher=Ideos|year=2018|isbn=978-3-9524742-5-9|editor-last=Kochenov|editor-first=Dimitry|edition= 3rd|location=|pages=|chapter=The Quality of Nationalities of Countries That Don\u2019t Exist: Measuring the Value of Unrecognized Nationalities|editor-last2=Lindeboom|editor-first2=Justin}}</ref> All nationalities receive a score from 0% to 100%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.de/nationalities-with-the-best-quality-of-life-2016-6?r=UK&IR=T|title= The 41 nationalities with the best quality of life |date= 2016-06-02 |website= www.businessinsider.de |access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Quality of Nationality Index factors.jpg|thumb|Weighted distribution of factors to calculate the QNI score]]\n\n=== Internal parameters and sources ===\nThe data is aggregated from various objective sources. The internal factors present the quality of life and opportunities for personal growth within the country of origin of the holder of nationality.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/239837/the-worlds-best-and-worst-nationalities-in-2018-including-south-africa/\n|title= The world's best and worst nationalities in 2018 \u2013 including South Africa |website= www.businesstech.co.za |access-date= 2018-08-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Human Development ====\nHuman Development is measured using the United Nations Development Programme Human Development Index ([[Human Development Index]]). The HDI was developed by Pakistani economist [[Mahbub ul Haq]] and Indian economist [[Amartya Sen]] which was further used to measure the country's development by the United Nations Development Program ([[UNDP]]). The index is based on the human development approach, developed by Ul Haq, often framed in terms of whether people are able to \"be\" and \"do\" desirable things in life. Examples include\u2014Being: well fed, sheltered, healthy; Doings: work, education, voting, participating in community life. Consequently, this index centres on three different human development areas: life expectancy at birth, expected years of education, and standard of living.\n\nThe QNI normalizes the HDI scores of the countries with which a particular nationality is associated to a 0-15% scale. The nationality of the highest-scoring country on the HDI gets the full 15% score, with the other nationalities being ranked proportionately.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ireland.co.nz/june-2016-ireland-ranks-6th-in-first-global-index-to-rank-quality-of-nationalities/ |title= Global Launch of the First Edition of the Henley & Partners \u2013 Kochenov Quality of Nationality Index |website= www.ireland.co.nz / |access-date= 2018-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://qz.com/698645/german-citizenship-is-ranked-the-most-valuable-in-the-world/|title= German citizenship is ranked the most valuable in the world|website= www. qz.com / |access-date= 2018-08-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic Strength ====\nEconomic Strength of a nationality is based on the [[Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) at [[Purchasing Power Parity]] (PPP) of the country with which the nationality is associated. It is calculated from the data that is provided by the [[International Monetary Fund]]. If there is no reliable [[Purchasing Power Parity]] data available, non-PPP data from the [[World Bank]] <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2018/05/the-richest-countries-with-the-weakest-passports/ |title= These are the richest countries with the weakest passports |date= 2018-05-02 |website= www.weforum.org |access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref> are used.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalityindex.com/methodology |title= Economic Strength |website= www.nationalityindex.com/ |access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref> GDP at PPP scores are normalized to a 0-15% scale, the largest economy receiving the full 15% score.\n\n==== Peace and Stability ====\nPeace and Stability are calculated using data by the annual [[Global Peace Index]] (GPI). The index is published by the Institute for Economics and Peace.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalityindex.com/methodology |title= Peace and Stability |website= www.nationalityindex.com/ |access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref> Peace and Stability accounts for 10% of the total QNI General Ranking scale. Also here the nationality which is associated with the most peaceful country receives the full 10%. The other nationalities are ranked proportionately on the basis of the ranking scale used by the GPI.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.emirates247.com/business/economy-finance/first-index-to-rank-quality-of-nationalities-2016-06-03-1.631911|title= First index to rank quality of nationalities\n |website= www.emirates247.com/ |access-date= 2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\n=== External parameters and sources ===\nExternal factors identify the quality of opportunities and diversity the holder of a nationality can pursue outside the country of origin.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2016/06/02/a-new-ranking-of-every-countrys-citizenship|title= A new ranking of every country's citizenship |date= 2016-06-02 |website= www.economist.com |access-date= 2018-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==== Diversity of Travel Freedom ====\nDiversity of Travel Freedom is based on how many destinations the holder of a particular nationality can visit without a visa or with a visa-on-arrival <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbr.co.nz/opinion/frances-macron-uses-culture-assert-worlds-top-soft-power-nationality|title= France's Macron uses culture to assert world's top 'soft power' nationality |website= www.nbr.co.nz|access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref> for short-term tourist or business purposes. The data is sourced from the International Air Transport Association [[IATA]]. The diversity of Travel Freedom accounts for 15% of the total QNI General Ranking scale.\n\n==== Weight of Travel Freedom ====\nWeight of Travel Freedom evaluates the quality of the travel freedom the holder of a nationality has without a visa or with a visa-on-arrival for short term visits. Unlike Diversity of Travel Freedom, which looks only at the number of destinations, Weight of Travel Freedom looks at the value of having visa-free or visa-on-arrival travel access to a particular country. This value is based on the Human Development (50%) and Economic Strength (50%) of each country destination.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalityindex.com/methodology|title= Quality of Nationality Index Methodology\n |website= www.nationalityindex.com/|access-date= 2018-08-06}}</ref> This is based on the presumption that for most people, having visa-free access to the United States of America is of higher value than having visa-free access to Sudan, for example. Weight of Travel Freedom accounts for 15% of the total QNI General Ranking scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundssociety.com/en/style/which-one-is-the-best-passport-to-have |title= Which One is the Best Passport to Have?\n |website= http://www.fundssociety.com/|access-date= 2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Diversity of Settlement Freedom ====\nDiversity of Settlement Freedom is based on the number of foreign countries in which the holder of a nationality can freely settle for at least 360 days with automatic access to work there.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jennysouthan/2018/04/26/worlds-top-nationalities-revealed-france-is-number-one-us-ranks-27/#b6a6b847d46f |title= World's Top Nationalities Revealed: France Is No. 1, U.S. Ranks 27 |date= 2018-04-26 |website= www.forbes.com |access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref> Diversity of Settlement Freedom accounts for 15% of the total QNI General Ranking scale. The most advanced example of a regional organization which allows nationals of its Member States to freely settle in each of the other Member States is the [[European Union]]. However, similar regional organizations which include free settlement among Member States are [[Mercosur|MERCOSUR]], the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]], and [[Economic Community of West African States|Economic Community of Western African States]]. Outside such regional organizations, [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] is the only country that allows almost all foreigners to freely settle and work in its country.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Quality of Nationality Index|last=Delcour|first=Laure|publisher=Ideos Publishing|year=2017|isbn=978-0-9935866-6-8|editor-last=Kochenov|editor-first=Dimitry|edition= 2nd|chapter=Georgia}}</ref> If there is a \u2018[[Hard Brexit]]\u2019, British citizens may lose their settlement and working rights to more than 30 of the world's leading countries, seriously affecting the quality of the British nationality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/travel/articles/949069/worlds-best-nationalists-revealed-france-winner|title=FRANCE is the world's best nationality according to new data \u2013 where does the UK rank?|date=2018-04-20|website=www.express.co.uk|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2016/06/02/a-new-ranking-of-every-countrys-citizenship|title=A new ranking of every country's citizenship|date=2016-06-02|website=www.economist.com|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==== Weight of Settlement Freedom ====\nWeight of Settlement Freedom evaluates the quality of the settlement freedom of the holder of a nationality. It does so by looking at the Human Development (50%) and Economic Strength (50%) of the countries to which the nationality holder has settlement access. Weight of Settlement Freedom accounts for 15% of the total QNI General Ranking scale.\n\nAs of 2017, France's quality of nationality is ranked the best in the world, according to the latest edition of the Quality of Nationality Index (QNI).<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Quality of Nationality Index|last=Platon|first=S\u00e9bastien|publisher=Ideos|year=2018|isbn=978-3-9524742-5-9|editor-last=Kochenov|editor-first=Dimitry|edition= 3rd|chapter=The French Nationality|editor-last2=Lindeboom|editor-first2=Justin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nbr.co.nz/opinion/frances-macron-uses-culture-assert-worlds-top-soft-power-nationality\n |title= France's Macron uses culture to assert world's top'soft power' nationality|date= 2016-05-29 |website= www.nbr.co.nz|access-date= 2018-08-08}}</ref>\nThe French nationality earned a score of 81.7% out of a possible 100%, fractionally ahead of Germany.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Quality of Nationality Index|last=Thym|first=Daniel|publisher=Ideos|year=2018|isbn=978-3-9524742-5-9|editor-last=Kochenov|editor-first=Dimitry|pages=|chapter=The German Nationality|editor-last2=Lindeboom|editor-first2=Justin}}</ref> While the difference between France's and Germany's results is relatively small, France's comparative advantage lies in its greater settlement freedom (attributable mainly to the country's former colonial empire<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jennysouthan/2018/04/26/worlds-top-nationalities-revealed-france-is-number-one-us-ranks-27/#b6a6b847d46f |title= World's Top Nationalities Revealed: France Is No. 1, U.S. Ranks 27 |date= 2018-04-26 |website=  www.forbes.com |access-date= 2018-07-30}}</ref>).\n\n== Results ==\nFrance's quality of nationality is ranked the best in the world, according to the latest edition of the Quality of Nationality Index (2018 data).<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nbr.co.nz/opinion/frances-macron-uses-culture-assert-worlds-top-soft-power-nationality |title= France's Macron uses culture to assert world's top'soft power' nationality|date= 2016-05-29 |website= www.nbr.co.nz|access-date= 2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/france/20191121-its-good-be-french-quality-nationality-index-settlement-freedom-kalin-kochenov|title=France excels in enabling its citizens to move abroad|date= 2019-11-22 |website= www.rfi.fr|access-date= 2019-12-07}}</ref>The French nationality earned a score of 83.5% out of a possible 100%, fractionally ahead of Germany and the Netherlands. While the difference between France's and Germany's result is relatively small, France's comparative advantage lies in its greater settlement freedom (attributable mainly to the country's former colonial empire<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jennysouthan/2018/04/26/worlds-top-nationalities-revealed-france-is-number-one-us-ranks-27/#b6a6b847d46f |title= World's Top Nationalities Revealed: France Is No. 1, U.S. Ranks 27 |date= 2018-04-26 |website=  www.forbes.com |access-date= 2018-08-28}}</ref>).\n\n=== Full ranking (2018) ===\n<div style=\"width:100%; height:40em; overflow:auto;border:none;\">\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable \" style=\"width:98%; margin-left:auto; margin-right:0px\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Citizenship !! Score\n|-\n| 1 ||{{flag|France}}|| 83.5%\n|-\n| 2 ||{{flag|Germany}}|| 82.8%\n|-\n| 2 ||{{flag|Netherlands}} || 82.8%\n|-\n| 3 ||{{flag|Denmark}} || 81.7%\n|-\n| 4 ||{{flag|Sweden}} || 81.5%\n|-\n| 4 ||{{flag|Norway}} || 81.5%\n|-\n| 5 ||{{flag|Iceland}} ||81.4%\n|-\n| 6 ||{{flag|Finland}} || 81.2%\n|-\n| 7 ||{{flag|Italy}} || 80.7%\n|-\n| 8 ||{{flag|United Kingdom}}|| 80.3%\n|-\n| 9 ||{{flag|Ireland}} || 80.2%\n|-\n| 10 ||{{flag|Spain}} || 80.0%\n|-\n| 11 ||{{flag|Switzerland}} || 79.8%\n|-\n| 11 ||{{flag|Belgium}} || 79.8%\n|-\n| 12 ||{{flag|Austria}} || 79.7%\n|-\n| 13 ||{{flag|Czech Republic}} || 79.0%\n|-\n| 13 ||{{flag|Portugal}} || 79.0%\n|-\n| 13 ||{{flag|Luxembourg}} || 79.0%\n|-\n| 14 ||{{flag|Liechtenstein}} ||78.9%\n|-\n| 15 ||{{flag|Slovenia}} || 78.6%\n|-\n| 16 ||{{flag|Malta}} || 77.6%\n|-\n| 17 ||{{flag|Hungary}} || 77.5%\n|-\n| 17 ||{{flag|Slovakia}} || 77.5%\n|-\n| 18 ||{{flag|Greece}} || 77.3%\n|-\n| 19 ||{{flag|Estonia}} || 77.1%\n|-\n| 20 ||{{flag|Poland}} || 77.0%\n|-\n| 20 ||{{flag|Lithuania}} || 77.0%\n|-\n| 20 ||{{flag|Latvia}}|| 77.0%\n|-\n| 21 ||{{flag|Cyprus}} ||75.3%\n|-\n| 22 ||{{flag|Romania}} || 75.2%\n|-\n| 23 ||{{flag|Bulgaria}} || 75.0%\n|-\n| 24 ||{{flag|Croatia}} || 73.8%\n|-\n